      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_18",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "2023",
        "bbox": [
          0.6233269605857337,
          0.2747093025389389,
          0.6443594644142664,
          0.2834302321994332
        ],
        "order": 14
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_17",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "2022",
        "bbox": [
          0.5468451240627866,
          0.27470930268428767,
          0.5697896745987812,
          0.283430232344782
        ],
        "order": 15
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_20",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The bullish mood on rate cuts spurred investors to push up stockmarkets. On December 1st the s&P 500 and the Dow Jones industrial average closed at their highest points this year (though they fell back in subsequent trading). The NASDAQ composite has not been as buoyant these past few weeks, but it has still risen by more than 35% this year.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5066921571179622,
          0.30803571423020787,
          0.7151051603893124,
          0.4651162788099616
        ],
        "order": 18
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Meanwhile, a federal judge imposed an injunction against Montana's statewide ban on TikTok. The ban was supposed to come into force in January, but the judge found that Montana was focused on \"targeting China's ostensible role in TikTok\", and that foreign policy \"is not an important Montana state interest\". The ban had been challenged by TikTok and free-speech advocates. Montana described the injunction as \"a preliminary matter\" in an ongoing process in which it would present \"a complete legal argument\" to the court.",
        "bbox": [
          0.0592734201610034,
          0.30803571446606814,
          0.26386232942436166,
          0.5436507936067887
        ],
        "order": 19
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_24",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "After being warned about \"greenwashing\", companies are now being told not to engage in Al-washing, or claiming a product or service has been created with artificial intelligence when it has not. Gary Gensler, the chairman of America's Securities and Exchange Commission, reminded firms that by law they are required to make \"truthful\" disclosures regarding their use of Al. Examples abound, but include a business that falsely claimed it had used \"Al machine learning\" to maximise revenues (some investors lost their life savings) and a startup that said it deployed Al to develop mobile apps (the work was mostly done by staff in India).",
        "bbox": [
          0.7304015362849872,
          0.3211805553928701,
          0.939105611123425,
          0.6229788939477802
        ],
        "order": 20
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_21",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Australia's economy grew by 2.1% in the third quarter on an annual basis, but was just 0.2% bigger than over the previous three months. The quarter-onquarter rate came in below forecasts and was the slowest pace in a year. Household spending was flat in the Lucky Country, as inflation, interest rates and the end of a tax-offset scheme took their toll on personal finances.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5086042065290471,
          0.4811046511318988,
          0.715105159528892,
          0.6220930230252885
        ],
        "order": 21
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The price of bitcoin surged past $44,000, its highest level in 20 months. It was boosted in part by investors betting that central banks will cut interest rates next year, which makes riskier assets more attractive. Gold, another asset that does well when interest rates are lower, hit a record high of $2,135 a troy ounce.",
        "bbox": [
          0.2848948381520902,
          0.5319767443055592,
          0.4818355676009719,
          0.6220930230252885
        ],
        "order": 22
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "China has started operating the world's first \"fourth-generation\" nuclear reactor, according to state media. The coastal plant in China's Shandong province generates power through a HTR-PM high-temperature, gas-cooled reactor, based on a modular design. Over the past ten years China has added 37 nuclear reactors to its energy mix (America has added two) and is aiming to install between another six and eight a year.",
        "bbox": [
          0.06081280087381808,
          0.5595238095931504,
          0.2657743801337704,
          0.7558139532285663
        ],
        "order": 23
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_26",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "DON'T",
        "bbox": [
          0.8565965591705088,
          0.6598837208508911,
          0.9005736135350361,
          0.6715116276956206
        ],
        "order": 25
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.09_page_009_25",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "BIBI...",
        "bbox": [
